# Master Of The Labyrinth
## Project Manifest

Version: 0.1
Status: Active

---

# Why are we making this game?

Master Of The Labyrinth is not a game about surviving traps.

It is a game about proving yourself worthy.

The player is not trying to defeat the Master.

The player is trying to become the next Master.

Every room...
Every trap...
Every decision...

...is part of a test.

The Labyrinth does not seek death.

It seeks someone capable of understanding it.

---

# Design Philosophy

Whenever a new mechanic is proposed, it must reinforce at least one of these principles.

If it does not, it should not be part of the game.

---

## 1. The Labyrinth is Alive

The Labyrinth is not a map.

It is a character.

It observes.

It reacts.

It tests.

Everything that happens inside it has a purpose.

---

## 2. Every Trap Must Be Fair

The player should never die without a chance to react.

Every trap must communicate itself through:

- Sound
- Environment
- Animation
- Timing

Failure should always teach something.

---

## 3. Knowledge Is Progress

There are no levels.

There is no experience system.

There are no skill trees.

The only real progression is the player's knowledge.

Learning the Labyrinth is becoming stronger.

---

## 4. Observation Is More Valuable Than Reflexes

Fast reactions are useful.

Observation is essential.

Players who pay attention to details should always have an advantage.

---

## 5. The Labyrinth Never Cheats

The Master challenges.

The Master does not deceive.

Randomness exists only to create new situations.

Never to create impossible situations.

---

## 6. Every Run Should Tell a Story

Players should remember situations.

Not statistics.

Examples:

"I escaped while limping."

"I heard the trap before seeing it."

"I almost reached the exit."

"I trusted the wrong corridor."

Those stories are the real reward.

---

## 7. Simplicity First

Complexity is earned.

Every mechanic must be understandable.

If an idea requires a long explanation,
it probably does not belong in the game.

---

## 8. The Environment Is The Interface

Avoid unnecessary HUD elements.

The world itself should communicate:

Danger.

Direction.

Events.

Secrets.

The player should learn to read the Labyrinth.

---

## 9. The Master Is Not The Enemy

The Master is the examiner.

The player is the candidate.

Death is failure.

Victory is recognition.

---

## 10. Becoming The Master

Escaping the Labyrinth is not the end.

It is merely the final proof.

The greatest reward is not freedom.

It is inheritance.

One day...

The player may become the next Master.

---

# Development Philosophy

This project values quality over quantity.

A single memorable room is better than ten forgettable ones.

A single excellent trap is better than twenty mediocre traps.

A mechanic only exists if it improves the experience.

---

# Internal Motto

"The Labyrinth does not punish.

It evaluates."

